	   <a name=96658209115004></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96658209115004><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=7&mid=96658209115004>Basics for new clerics</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=7&mid=96658209115004#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Aug 18th 3:01 AM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.43]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>First thing when starting a cleric is the race. The best two are the dwarf and the high elf for several reasons. The dwarf offers the best physical stats and good WIS, the high elf the best psychic stats at expense of STR. The other advantages are: both can wear small armor, and both are not KoS to many people, and they have infravision.<br>Second thing, mostly if you have been playing before, is to get a friend, who is a fighter type. With one constant partner you can not only level fast and go, where you cant go alone, you are also able to play fairly regularly and have soemone you can trust. After level 30 (in my experience), has the time come to join larger groups, but then you have the power to get around without being killed, can do a lot of things, and want to socialize and explore anyway.<br>It took me 5 hours for a level from 25 to 29, so you can get to a medium level fairly quickly with a partner. This is a good thing, if you cant play like a student, but as a worker bee like me, which amounts to 15 hours per week.<br><br>Clerics are able to do a lot of things with their spells, which is better learned with only one partner, when you have to do them. In a larger group your role as the healer is practically a given, so you will never use certain tactics, or be allowed to pull off a stunt (which is part of the fun, if you ask me). Examples, what you can do include camp-breaking, crowd control and melee (up to about 25th level). Many have forgotten, that you dont have to have the best spell to do a thing, and that there are alternative ways how to go about a problem, even if they are not as "clean" as you are used to...<br><br>Good zones for level 1 to 10 are Greater Faydark, Butcherblock and Misty Thicket (I got to 7th in BB, and moved then to Misty until 9th). From 11 to 20 there are the Karanas, the Oasis and Highpass Hold (I was from 9th to 14th in WK, then moved to Oasis till 20th). From 21 to 30 there is SK, Lake of Ill Omen, Rathe Mountains and Najena (I was till 24th mainly in SK with a few forays here and there, then switched to the Lake until 29th). After that you can go to many places, including all medium level dungeons (I went to the Frontier Mountains, did corrupt guards, raided Sol A and Lower Guk til 40th).<br><br>The best weapon to train is probably 1h blunt and forget 2h, since you will soon carry some WIS or mana item in one hand. The best armor is plate (not possible to get for real beginners), but the quest armor can be gotten from 20 on (this is mostly a cash problem). Later on (after 30), you can sacrifice AC for mana, but before that I would suggest to go with as high AC as possible, so you can double up as a fighter, if needs be.<br><br>And here is a last suggestion for you: when you get into a dungeon group, it is a very good thing to have a second cleric on the team (you will see why, once you have the opportunity :) ).<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
