<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%>
	   <a name=98508108668026></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f98508108668026><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=7&mid=98508108668026>RE: If you want to be a cleric...</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=7&mid=98508108668026#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=39002><span id=Scholar>Ismena</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>40 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Mar 20th 4:38 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Quoting Anonymous:&nbsp;&nbsp;You have two jobs 1) Buff with AC and HP buffs 2) Keep everyone alive. <br><br>I wholeheartedly disagree.  As a 54 cleric, I want to assert that you have not two jobs but only one: to keep everyone alive.  Of course this is done most efficiently with buffs, which is why I really, really insist on buffing my entire party (unless an insane puller won't let me med), but if you're keeping everyone healthy even through the bad pulls, then they shouldn't complain.<br><br>Here's why you buff people as a means of keeping them alive:<br>1.  It makes them happy.  Don't write this off; there's a psychological advantage to it.  People who have been buffed may be able to play a little more capably as they watch the HP bar a bit less, or get mad at you less often.<br>2.  It's mana-efficient.  Say your tank has 2000 hp.  You start casting Complete Heal and should have timed it to be sure it goes off when he's down to 20% (400hp), making the CH worth 1600hp.  But with your buffs, he's got 2800hp, and a CH is now worth 2240hp, a 40% improvement.  You also CH a shaman who is cannibalizing, with a similar improvement in mana efficiency.<br>3.  Buffing should keep the enchanter alive longer.  Your enchanter is naturally endowed with maybe 800hp and takes three seconds for two mobs to kill.  Buff him up to 1600 and now he takes 6 seconds to kill.  That may be enough time to get a Remedy off, especially if you keep that puppy targeted whenever you aren't in the process of healing someone else.  Is this mana-efficient?  Well, consider the mana cost of six rezzes.<br>4.  For the other party members who aren't taking a lot of damage, you know perfectly well that given a bad pull, they will be taking life-threatening damage, and will very much need those buffs.  They should have them before they need them.<br>5.  A party whom you haven't buffed will hate your guts.  Buff them or they'll dismiss you as an eBayed hack and do their best never to group with you again.  I'm not kidding.<br><br>I would like to add a few (haha) words on mana and buffing:<br>Often the party expects me to buff no matter how much mana it takes nor how little mana I have.  This is crazy.  A group Hero costs me almost 20% of my mana.  If I'm at 60% mana, I just won't do it.  In spite of everything I said above, I have to have mana to heal, but I know that buffing my party even once will make the puller confident to run off and pull something back, and I may just run out of mana, and we all die.  I don't enjoy corpse retrievals, and I don't like losing xp or hunting time.  I prefer to med up to at least 85%, even better to 95%, before buffing, and I cast only one buff at a time, so I don't lose more than about 15% of my mana.<br><br>And why do I want to be full mana all the time, even though a typical pull only takes up 30%?  Because sooner or later a pull goes bad, and I shall need that other 70% to keep us alive.  Unfortunately, most pullers don't see it that way, and are impatient to bring the next mob.  I once said to my puller, "You can bounce me back and forth from 40 to 0 mana, and so far we're doing okay, or you can let me med to full and bounce me from 100m to 60m.  Exact same downtime, exact same pull rate, exact same time to med back up, but which do you think is safer?"  He saw my point and without further argument slowed down the rate of pulls for a while to let me build up mana.<br><br>Besides, he made the cleric happy.<br>&nbsp;<br>Ismena, 65 Cleric<br>Forbydyn, Rogue<br>Alethea, Bard<br>Darcye, Wizard<br>Darcie, Ranger<br>Tihmm, Enchanter<br>Prexus<br>That's =Doctor= Barbie to you</td></tr>
